---
import Base from "../../layouts/Base.astro";
import TracePlayer from "../../islands/TracePlayer.svelte";
import LessonNav from "../../components/LessonNav.astro";
import buggy from "../../../derived/booleanops/buggy.trace.json";
import procedural from "../../../derived/booleanops/procedural.trace.json";

// Buggy first: watch it fail in real state, then watch the fix.
const registers = [buggy, procedural];
---

<Base title="and / or / not — GlassBox" description="x == 1 or 2 is read as (x == 1) or 2 and returns 2 — always truthy. Compare against both values.">
  <LessonNav slug="booleanops" position="top" />

  <h1>and / or / not — and what or returns</h1>
  <p class="lede">Reading <code>x == 1 or 2</code> as 'x is 1 or 2' is the classic boolean trap. Python groups it as <code>(x == 1) or 2</code>, and <code>or</code> hands back an operand, not always a tidy <code>True</code>/<code>False</code>. Watch what actually lands in <code>match</code>.</p>

  <TracePlayer registers={registers} client:visible />

  <section class="explain card">
    <h2>What you are looking at</h2>
    <p>Watch <code>match</code> closely — the value may not even be a boolean.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Buggy</strong> — <code>match = x == 1 or 2</code> becomes <code>False or 2</code>, and <code>or</code> returns its first truthy operand: the integer <code>2</code>. Not <code>True</code> — the number 2, which is truthy, so any <code>if match:</code> would always fire.</li>
      <li><strong>Procedural</strong> — <code>match = x == 1 or x == 2</code> compares against both values in full and gives a real <code>False</code>. Each side of an <code>or</code> needs to be a complete condition.</li>
    </ul>
    <p class="fineprint">Every state you see came from running the program under CPython's tracer at build time — see <a href="../../verification/">how GlassBox stays honest</a>.</p>
  </section>
  <LessonNav slug="booleanops" position="bottom" />
</Base>

<style>
  .explain { margin-top: 1.4rem; }
  .explain ul { margin: 0.6rem 0; padding-left: 1.1rem; }
  .explain li { margin: 0.5rem 0; }
  .fineprint { color: var(--ink-faint); font-size: 0.9rem; margin-bottom: 0; }
</style>
